        <svcproc svcproctype="repair" graphiccount="1">
            <title>SERVICE PROCEDURE</title>
            <para>Inspect the fan drive for a green dot possibly on the fins on the backside (engine side) of the fan
                drive. If there is a
                <emph type="bold">green paint dot</emph>
                the fan drive does
                <emph type="bold">not</emph>
                need to be replaced.
            </para>
            <para>If there is
                <emph type="bold">no green paint dot</emph>
                proceed as follows:
            </para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the existing fan drive from the engine.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove and retain the fan blade and fasteners.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install the fan blade on the replacement fan drive. Lubricate the fastener threads and
                    tighten the fasteners to 13 to 16 Lbf-Ft (18 to 22 NM).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install the fan drive on the engine. Lubricate the threads and tighten to 120 to 150
                    Lbf-Ft (163 to 203 NM).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f009091" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g009091.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="392px"
                         resolution="300"/>
                <caption>Figure 1. Engine Side of Fan Drive with Typical Location of Green Paint Dot</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. Location of serial number</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
        </svcproc>
        <svcproc svcproctype="repair" graphiccount="0">
            <title>Service Procedure</title>
            <specpara>
                <important>
                    <para>You are required to destroy the fan drive that was replaced so that it is no longer
                        operational prior to disposal.
                    </para>
                </important>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Place the fan drive on a secure and solid surface.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">With a hammer and punch, strike the bi-metal element sharply and off center so that it
                    is visually distorted and the fan drive can no longer be serviced.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Dispose of the fan drive in accordance with any local, state and Federal requirements.
                </para>
            </step1>
        </svcproc>
        <laborinfo>
            <para>Operation number must appear on all claims.</para>
            <para>Record the fan drive serial number in the text of your claim. The serial number is located on the
                perimeter of the fan drive housing (Figure 1, Item 1) along with the Borg-Warner part number and the
                International part number. An example of the serial number:
                <emph type="bold">DJL 01074</emph>
            </para>
